<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-364-690  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 364 690.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  April 23 1990 v7 n16 p10(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>PS/2 Models 65, 80 recalled. (IBM suspends shipment of its newPS/2 model 65 and 80 microcomputers due to SCSI adapter problems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sexton, Tara.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (product development).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Product:   IBM PS/2 65 (Microcomputer) (defects)IBM PS/2 80 (Microcomputer) (defects).andO;Topic:     MicrocomputersDefectsProduct RecallNew ProductSmall Computer Systems Interface.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Tara SextonandM;IBM last week suspended shipment of its new PS/2 Models 65 and 80 computersbecause of a problem with the SCSI adapter included in those machines,company officials said.andM;The company also halted delivery of the SCSI adapter until the end of themonth, when a version equipped with a fix is planned for production.andM;During volume ramp-up and ongoing quality testing, IBM engineers determinedthat a limited number of the Small Computer Systems Interface (SCSI) hostadapters -- which IBM has been developing for nearly three years -- may failduring certain data-transfer operations.andP;  The result could be a loss of datawithout any indication of an error, said Rob Wilson, an IBM spokesman inWhite Plains, N.Y.andM;&quot;There are no problems with the PS/2 systems or any of the SCSI peripheralsthat connect to them,&quot; Wilson said.andP;  &quot;The problem has been isolated to theadapter.&quot;andM;A problem with the SCSI host adapter, however, may spell trouble for the newsystems, which have generated interest because of their SCSI capabilities,dealers said.andM;&quot;SCSI has been the big selling point for the new IBM machines,&quot; said ScottSayre, a systems consultant for Entre Computer Corp. in West Newton, Mass.andO;&quot;[IBM] must be swallowing hard right now.&quot;andM;IBM has labeled the recall &quot;precautionary,&quot; and is notifying all dealers andusers who have purchased systems equipped with the defective adapters, saidWilson.andM;Because IBM never reveals the number of systems it has shipped, dealers lastweek could not say how long the recall process will take.andM;However, most dealers said IBM caught the problem in plenty of time.andM;&quot;I haven't sold enough of them to worry about a lot of disgruntledcustomers,&quot; said one dealer.andM;&quot;Most of the machines out in the field are on spec,&quot; added Mark Cuban,president of Micro Solutions Inc. in Dallas.andP;  &quot;This is IBM's way of fixingmistakes before they become real problems.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>